CommonFields.Title: The effect of silica nanoparticles on the morphology, mechanical properties and thermal degradation kinetics of PMMA
Author: Saladino, M.L.
Motaung, T.E.
Luyt, A.S.
Spinella, A.
Nasillo, G.
Caponetti, E.
CommonFields.Location: Department of Chemistry “S.Cannizzaro”, University of Palermo, Parco d'Orleans II-Viale delle Scienze pad.17, Palermo I-90128, Italy

Drying-Evaporation.Description: PMMA and silica were dried overnight under static vacuum before processing

MoldingInfo.Description: Samples were melt-pressed into 1 mm thick sheets

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description: TEM micrographs were acquired using a JEM-2100 electron microscope, equipped with an X-ray energy dispersive spectrometer for analysis of elements, operating at a 200 kV accelerating voltage. A few tens of a milligram of the powders were dispersed in 2 mL of isopropanol and a small drop of the dispersion was deposited on a 300 mesh carbon-coated copper grid, which was introduced into the TEM analysis chamber after complete solvent evaporation.

Fourier_Transform_Infrared_Spectroscopy.Description: The FTIR spectra were recorded in the transmittance mode at different temperatures during the thermal degradation process.

XRay_Diffraction_and_Scattering.Description: XRD patterns were recorded in the 2-70° 2-theta range at steps of 0.05° and a counting time of 5 s/step on a Philips PW 1050 diffractometer, equipped with a Cu tube and a scintillation detector beam. The X-ray generator worked at 40 kV and 30 mA.

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: The analyses were done under flowing nitrogen at a constant flow rate of 20 mL/min. Samples (5-10 mg) were heated from 25 to 600°C at different heating rates.

Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Equipment: Bruker Avance II 400 MHz (9.4 T) spectrometer
